		<description><![CDATA[I followed Samba for Arch Linux and the Arch Linux Arm Guide to Samba to get Samba working on my Raspberry Pi. This version of Arch Arm is using systemd to manage services, so there is no more /etc/rc.conf file to edit and no rc.d command available to start anything (as the Arch Linux Arm [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/raspberrypi1.jpeg"><img src="/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/raspberrypi1.jpeg" alt="" title="raspberrypi" width="204" height="247" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-490" /></a><br />
<a href="/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/arch-linux-arm.png"><img src="/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/arch-linux-arm.png" alt="Arch Liux Arm" title="arch-linux-arm" width="400" height="89" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-484" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/arch-linux-arm.png 400w, /wp-content/uploads/2012/11/arch-linux-arm-300x66.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px" /></a><br />
I followed <a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Samba">Samba for Arch Linux</a> and the <a href="http://archlinuxarm.org/support/guides/applications/samba">Arch Linux Arm Guide to Samba</a> to get Samba working on my <a href="http://www.raspberrypi.org/">Raspberry Pi</a>.</p>
<p>This version of Arch Arm is using <a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Systemd">systemd</a> to manage services, so there is no more <code>/etc/rc.conf</code> file to edit and no <code>rc.d</code> command available to start anything (as the Arch Linux Arm Guide instructs). One simply types <code>systemctl start smbd.service</code> to make it go (after configuring <code>/etc/samba/smb.conf</code>, of course).</p>
]]></content:encoded>
